<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99019137289873></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99019137289873><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=4&mid=99019137289873>RE: twisting</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=27649><span id=Guru>Palarran</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>116 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, May 18th 9:09 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The problem with using socials to twist several songs with a single key is that you won't be able to stop the social in the middle if needed.  While I do find myself cycling through the same three songs a good portion of the time (whatever 3 songs I have chosen for that situation), I have very different ways of handling 1, 2, and 3+ mob situations and I need to be able to switch between them as mobs join the fight or are killed.  I also need to pull mobs off casters often, typically by tossing a charm song into the mix.  If I were using socials to automatically twist songs it could take me up to 12 seconds to pull a mob off a caster instead of 3 seconds.<br><br>On a somewhat related note, twisting songs will be easier if you map your song/spell keys to be single keystrokes.  I found mapping my songs to F1-F8 (and then mapping the target self/party member keys that used to be there to ctrl-F1 to ctrl-F8) to work extremely well.  As a bard I am singing songs and using hotkeys much more often than I am targetting party members, since nearly all the songs I use are self-only, group, or used on mobs.<br><br>Changing keyboard shortcuts will make the changes for all characters, but after I adjusted I found I liked being able to cast spells with my other characters using single keystrokes too.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99039100755952></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99039100755952><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=4&mid=99039100755952>RE: twisting</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, May 20th 4:36 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Yes, try not to use socials to twist more than one song by using one key. Sure it helps you not screw up (because of lag or simple mistiming), but when the time comes up to switch to a different song, or end the song there, you'll find yourself helpless. For one, if you end up having to run, you'll have to wait till the end of the social, to switch to Selo's and jet to the next zone. Furthermore, when your song is interrupted from a bash or whatnot, it will screw up the timing of your hotkey.<br><br>My suggestion is to simply set your 8 songs to hot keys, and then set the user defined keys to either the F1-8 keys or the numpad. I, myself, use "wasd" as my movements since I play a number of FPS games as well. When I do this, I simply place my user defined keys on my numpad, and can twist songs rather easily.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

